1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,530
A big thinker always visualizes what can be done in the future.

2
00:00:04,720 --> 00:00:06,929
He isn't stuck with the present.

3
00:00:07,440 --> 00:00:08,449
2.

4
00:00:08,800 --> 00:00:11,570
How much is a customer worth?

5
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:17,010
A department store executive was addressing a conference of merchandise managers.

6
00:00:17,120 --> 00:00:26,929
She was saying, I may be a little old-fashioned, but I belong to the school that believes the best way to get customers to come back is to give them friendly,

7
00:00:26,960 --> 00:00:28,290
courteous service.

8
00:00:28,639 --> 00:00:34,610
One day I was walking through our store when I overheard a salesperson arguing with a customer.

9
00:00:34,720 --> 00:00:37,250
The customer left in quite a huff.

10
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:48,770
Afterward, the salesperson said to another, I'm not going to let a $1.98 customer take up all my time and make me take the store apart trying to find him what he wants.

11
00:00:48,960 --> 00:00:50,610
He's simply not worth it.

12
00:00:51,120 --> 00:00:53,969
I walked away, the executive continued.

13
00:00:54,080 --> 00:00:56,770
But I couldn't get that remark out of my mind.

14
00:00:57,120 --> 00:01:04,530
It is pretty serious, I thought, when our salespeople think of customers as being in the $1.98 category.

15
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:08,610
I decided right then that this concept must be changed.

16
00:01:08,800 --> 00:01:18,209
When I got back to my office, I called our research director and asked him to find out how much the average customer spent in our store last year.

17
00:01:18,480 --> 00:01:21,409
The figure he came up with surprised even me.

18
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:30,370
According to our research director's careful calculation, the typical customer spent $362 in our establishment.

19
00:01:30,720 --> 00:01:37,010
The next thing I did was call a meeting of all supervisory personnel and explain the incident to them.

20
00:01:37,280 --> 00:01:40,449
Then I showed them what a customer is really worth.

21
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:46,209
Once I got these people to see that a customer is not to be valued on a single sale,

22
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:51,409
but rather on an annual basis, customer service definitely improved.

23
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:57,010
The point made by the retailing executive applies to any kind of business.

24
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:00,209
It's repeat business that makes the profit.

25
00:02:00,480 --> 00:02:04,209
Often there's no profit at all on the first several sales.

26
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:09,889
Look at the potential expenditures of the customers, not just what they buy today.

27
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:16,290
Putting a big value on customers is what converts them into big regular patrons.

28
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:20,209
Attaching little value to customers sends them elsewhere.

